===Etymology 1===
{{zh-forms|alt=𡈼-ancient}}

From {{inh|zh|sit-pro|*(p/b)ljaŋ||straight; straighten}} (STEDT; {{zh-ref|Schuessler, 2003, 2007}}). Compare {{cog|my|ဖြောင့်|t=straight}}, as well as the following Chinese terms:
* {{och-l|𡈼|good, virtuous; to be good at}}
* {{och-l|庭|straight (of growing grain), upright (of morality); courtyard}}
* {{och-l|梃|stick, staff, club}}
* {{och-l|筳|bamboo rod}}
* {{och-l|鋌|metal rod, ingot}}
* {{och-l|珽|jade scepter}}

The Sino-Tibetan root is [[allofam]]ic with {{cog|sit-pro|*(p/b)ljaŋ|t=plank, palm, flat surface, wing}} (whence {{och-l|平|flat, even}}) and {{cog|sit-pro|*(p/b)liŋ|t=full; to fill}} (whence {{och-l|盈|to fill; full, surplus}}), with the semantic core of these roots being a "complete realization of a dimensional quality".

The intensifier usage “quite; very” is most likely a grammaticalized usage from “outstanding; prominent” ({{zh-ref|Liu, 2008}}; {{zh-ref|Yang, 2021}}). Alternatively, it may be from {{bor|zh|mnc|ᡨᡝᠨ||extreme}} ({{zh-ref|Aixinjueluo, 1993}}).

